ce:section.ce:para:
The assessment of drug loading and release efficiency is critical in evaluating the potential of targeted drug delivery systems. In this study, Doxorubicin (DOX) was chosen as an anti-cancer agent to examine the HA-DOX-GQD@BTNPs system, focusing on two distinct bond types: Ester and Amide bonding. The drug loading efficiency was determined based on a standard absorbance curve at 480 nm. The HA-DOX-GQD@BTNPs(amide) showcased a loading efficiency of 82.3 %, while HA-DOX-GQD@BTNPs(ester) exhibited a loading efficiency of 81.2 %. Both materials exhibit a high loading capacity, with values of 26.7 % and 22.8 % respectively, as summarized in Table 2
                        . These data highlight the significant role that GQD modification plays in this system. Owing to the resonance structure of GQD, doxorubicin is incorporated into the system via π-π stacking, which facilitates robust drug loading capacity [37]. The pH-trigger drug release behavior was further explored in Phosphate Buffered Saline (PBS) at pH 7.4 and 5.0, mimicking the extracellular and intracellular pH environments of cancer cells, respectively [38]. Drug release profiles, monitored through UV–Visible spectroscopy (Fig. 5
                        ), demonstrated that HA-DOX-GQD@BTNPs(amide) released 11.2 % of DOX at pH 7.4 and 45.8 % at pH 5.0 over a 48-hour period. Conversely, HA-DOX-GQD@BTNPs(ester) released 10.2 % of DOX at pH 7.4 and 46.1 % at pH 5.0 over the identical duration. Although the drug release from both systems is fairly comparable, the findings align with previous studies, suggesting that the drug release mechanism from GQDs renders HA-DOX-GQD@BTNPs an acid-sensitive release system. Remarkably, doxorubicin was released in larger quantities in lower pH solutions [39]. The study also delved into the impact of HA grafting on drug release behavior. As depicted in Fig. 4a and b, drug release did not attain equilibrium until the third day. This slow releasing phenomenon is ascribed to the favorable pharmacokinetic properties of HA [40,41].
